# Section development standards

## Section requirements

Every section must include:

- `{% schema %}` tag with valid JSON
- Proper HTML semantic structure
- Tailwind utility classes for styling
- Translation keys for all text

## Section patterns

**Basic section structure:**

```liquid
{% liquid
  assign section_id = section.settings.custom_id | default: section.id
%}

<section
  id="{{ section_id }}"
  class="relative"
  style="
    padding-top: {{ section.settings.padding_top }}px;
    padding-bottom: {{ section.settings.padding_bottom }}px;
  "
>
  <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
    {% content_for 'blocks' %}
  </div>
</section>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "t:names.section_name",
  "tag": "section",
  "class": "section-name",
  "blocks": [
    {"type": "@theme"},
    {"type": "@app"}
  ],
  "settings": [
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_top",
      "label": "t:settings.padding",
      "min": 0,
      "max": 100,
      "default": 40,
      "unit": "px"
    }
  ],
  "presets": [
    {
      "name": "t:names.section_name"
    }
  ]
}
{% endschema %}
```

## Styling with Tailwind

- Use Tailwind utility classes for all styling
- Use inline styles for dynamic values (padding, colors, etc.)
- Use Tailwind responsive prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`) for responsive design
- Use `container` class for page-width containers
- Combine Tailwind classes for complex layouts (grid, flex, etc.)

## Performance patterns

- Use `{% liquid %}` for multiline logic
- Lazy load images with `loading="lazy"`
- Use Tailwind classes instead of custom CSS
- Use inline styles only for dynamic values from settings

